05:03.839 --> 05:06.374
♪ Can you save me ♪

05:06.408 --> 05:08.442
♪ from this nothing
I've become? ♪

05:08.477 --> 05:10.444
♪ it's just something
that I've done ♪

05:10.479 --> 05:12.513
♪ I never meant
to cause you worry ♪

05:12.547 --> 05:14.482
♪ don't you blame me ♪

05:14.516 --> 05:16.417
♪ for this nothing
I've become ♪

05:16.451 --> 05:18.518
♪ it's just something
that I've done ♪

05:18.553 --> 05:21.284
♪ I never meant to show you
my mistakes ♪

05:26.140 --> 05:27.841
Is that your pedal foot?

05:27.875 --> 05:29.609
Ha ha.
Very funny.

05:29.644 --> 05:31.445
Annie's a fast driver.

05:31.479 --> 05:33.947
My sister wants us to do
the Marine Corps Marathon.

05:33.981 --> 05:35.281
Training started
last night.

05:35.315 --> 05:36.749
Is she married?

05:36.783 --> 05:38.351
Yeah.

05:38.385 --> 05:39.719
Hmm.

05:39.753 --> 05:41.788
What?

05:41.822 --> 05:43.089
Nothing.

05:43.124 --> 05:46.492
It's just that
in 35% of failed marriages

05:46.527 --> 05:48.294
the wife usually takes up
a sport or a pastime

05:48.328 --> 05:50.196
as a precursor to divorce.

05:50.230 --> 05:52.699
Although running is a really
great way to work things out.

05:52.733 --> 05:56.035
Besides, it's cheaper
than therapy, right?

05:56.069 --> 05:58.537
Okay, so, Annie, you're going
to use your Smithsonian NOC

05:58.572 --> 06:00.305
to infiltrate NASA.

06:00.340 --> 06:01.840
Great, I can use all that
knowledge I got at Space Camp

06:01.874 --> 06:02.874
when I was 12.

06:02.909 --> 06:04.475
I had no idea
you were a space geek.

06:04.510 --> 06:05.943
Get to know me.

06:05.978 --> 06:08.012
It's the final frontier.

06:08.046 --> 06:10.347
Space, I mean.
Not me.

06:10.381 --> 06:13.683
Reva, what do you think
of space exploration?

06:13.718 --> 06:15.017
If you look
at the numbers,

06:15.052 --> 06:17.253
the NASA missions
waste in inordinate amount

06:17.287 --> 06:18.688
of our nation's
science budget.

06:18.722 --> 06:20.289
Do you honestly think
you can put a price

06:20.323 --> 06:23.058
on bold explorations
of new frontiers in space?

06:23.092 --> 06:24.393
I try to.

06:24.427 --> 06:27.362
I have a spreadsheet here
if you'd like to see it.

06:27.396 --> 06:28.830
Okay, mission.

06:28.864 --> 06:32.300
Annie, you'll head down to NASA
headquarters on "E" street.

06:32.334 --> 06:35.170
There's a Mars day
reception in the lobby.

06:35.204 --> 06:37.206
NASA employees and their
families will be there.

06:37.240 --> 06:39.675
You'll take the oral histories
of four NASA staffers

06:39.710 --> 06:41.811
who contributed to the
maintenance of the satellite.

06:41.845 --> 06:43.279
And I'll take your video

06:43.314 --> 06:45.582
and use facial
and body language

06:45.616 --> 06:46.883
micro-expression analysis

06:46.918 --> 06:48.385
to hone in
on potential suspects.

06:48.420 --> 06:50.488
So you're gonna watch my
interviews and look for tells,

06:50.522 --> 06:52.156
like in poker?

06:52.191 --> 06:54.024
It's not a primitive gut
instinct like in a card game.

06:54.059 --> 06:55.259
It works.

06:55.293 --> 06:58.061
Annie, you'll ask
four general questions.

06:58.096 --> 07:00.029
Three of which are lead-ups
to the control trigger question.

07:00.064 --> 07:01.197
And one more thing,

07:01.231 --> 07:03.065
budget cuts at NASA
have been severe.

07:03.100 --> 07:05.234
So don't be disappointed
if morale--

07:05.269 --> 07:06.802
Isn't as high as yours.

07:06.837 --> 07:08.837
Okay.

07:29.194 --> 07:32.263
You're still here
with us regular folk.

07:32.298 --> 07:34.433
Bureaucracy never
ceases to amaze me.

07:34.467 --> 07:36.234
I had to fill out 12 forms

07:36.269 --> 07:38.503
just to get this key card
for the seventh floor,

07:38.538 --> 07:41.540
where I have to fill out
more forms.

07:44.444 --> 07:47.780
NASA wants us to investigate
scientists and astronauts.

07:47.814 --> 07:49.248
Well, if NASA's
requesting it,

07:49.283 --> 07:50.383
it's an internal audit,

07:50.417 --> 07:52.318
so you're not breaching
CIA charter.

07:52.353 --> 07:53.753
It still feels weird.

07:53.787 --> 07:56.355
Because it's Americans
or because it's NASA?

07:56.390 --> 07:57.623
Both.

07:57.657 --> 07:59.458
[Elevator dings]

07:59.492 --> 08:00.792
Joan knows how you feel.

08:00.827 --> 08:03.195
That's probably
why she picked you.

08:03.229 --> 08:04.663
Why is that?

08:04.698 --> 08:07.967
Because she knows you care
enough to get this right.

08:08.001 --> 08:09.168
[Electronic beeping]

08:09.202 --> 08:10.536
Now I don't know
if you caught that,

08:10.570 --> 08:12.271
but I just hit seven.

08:15.975 --> 08:18.009
My opponents
on the intelligence committee

08:18.044 --> 08:19.310
are gaining momentum.

08:19.345 --> 08:20.678
They're prepared to ask
for an investigation

08:20.713 --> 08:22.513
and hearings into Arthur
as early as next week.

08:22.548 --> 08:24.415
At least that's what
we're hearing.

08:24.449 --> 08:26.216
Maybe you know something else.

08:26.251 --> 08:27.684
Chet?

08:30.788 --> 08:32.722
Are you sure
this is decaf?

08:32.756 --> 08:36.025
Positive.

08:36.059 --> 08:37.961
Yeah.
Don't worry about hearings.

08:37.996 --> 08:40.097
Those clowns
on the intelligence committee

08:40.131 --> 08:42.000
have to justify
their jobs.

08:42.034 --> 08:43.635
You're in good hands
with me.

08:43.669 --> 08:45.170
So listen,
I have a tennis date

08:45.205 --> 08:46.538
in Hilton Head.

08:46.573 --> 08:48.541
We'll revisit
when I get back.

08:54.481 --> 08:56.549
I'm confused.

08:56.583 --> 08:59.518
Are we rescheduling
the meeting?

08:59.552 --> 09:03.054
Or was that the meeting?

09:03.088 --> 09:06.657
[Upbeat music]

09:06.691 --> 09:14.698
♪ ♪

09:22.874 --> 09:24.709
How did you come
to work for NASA?

09:24.743 --> 09:25.944
I was a double major

09:25.978 --> 09:28.046
in Physics and
Aeronautical Engineering.

09:28.081 --> 09:30.683
Not everyone can work on
ozone mapping spectrometers.

09:30.717 --> 09:32.251
With a minor
in Applied Mathematics.

09:32.286 --> 09:34.521
Air Force.
Fly, fight, win.

09:34.555 --> 09:38.892
I had PhDs in Musical Theory
and practical philosophy.

09:41.328 --> 09:44.163
I've always wanted
to work for NASA

09:44.197 --> 09:46.699
since I was
a little boy.

09:46.733 --> 09:50.101
What are you working on
specifically right now?

09:50.136 --> 09:52.637
T.O.M.S. volcanic emissions,
ozone mapping.

09:52.671 --> 09:54.238
I'm an astronaut.

09:56.642 --> 09:59.844
I supervise
a team of technicians

09:59.879 --> 10:01.613
in the satellite
maintenance office.

10:01.647 --> 10:03.616
We always have
a contingency plan,

10:03.650 --> 10:06.786
and no program is green lit

10:06.820 --> 10:08.922
until we know every solution

10:08.956 --> 10:10.591
to every possible
externality.

10:10.625 --> 10:12.660
Where do you see yourself
in five years?

10:12.694 --> 10:13.928
Out of H.Q. in D.C.

10:13.962 --> 10:15.597
and down to Canaveral
where the action happens.

10:15.631 --> 10:17.598
Space.

10:17.633 --> 10:20.402
Did I mention to you
I was an astronaut?

10:20.436 --> 10:22.004
Can I--I'm sorry,
can I go now?

10:22.038 --> 10:23.172
I'm a NASA guy,

10:23.206 --> 10:24.807
so I'll probably
be working right here.

10:24.842 --> 10:26.476
Tell her how close
you came to serving

10:26.510 --> 10:28.979
on the Presidential Commission
for Space Exploration.

10:29.013 --> 10:31.848
That's not a plant.
He's my son, Charlie.

10:31.883 --> 10:34.784
My dad should be
in the Smithsonian.

10:34.819 --> 10:36.953
Basically started working
for NASA when he was ten.

10:36.988 --> 10:39.990
I saw the Apollo 15 space
launch at Cape Canaveral.

10:40.024 --> 10:41.292
Really?

10:41.326 --> 10:43.126
Yes, my folks drove down
from Charlottesville

10:43.161 --> 10:45.996
in our Ford Country Squire
station wagon.

10:46.030 --> 10:47.430
What's your favorite
mission, Charlie?

10:47.465 --> 10:48.465
Pioneer Ten.

10:48.499 --> 10:49.766
Back from the dead

10:49.800 --> 10:51.835
and 7 billion miles away.

10:51.869 --> 10:52.902
And still going.

10:52.937 --> 10:53.904
See ya, Earth.

10:53.938 --> 10:55.639
I'm with Carl Sagan on that.

10:55.673 --> 10:57.408
We're just a pale-blue dot.

10:57.442 --> 10:59.310
Excuse me.

10:59.344 --> 11:01.980
I oversee all multimedia
projects at the Smithsonian,

11:02.014 --> 11:03.315
and the first I've heard
of this film

11:03.349 --> 11:05.684
is a phone call I got
about 15 minutes ago.

11:05.718 --> 11:07.519
Who exactly signed off
on your project?

11:07.553 --> 11:10.155
Dennis Stephens.

11:10.189 --> 11:12.857
I have no idea
who that is.

11:12.892 --> 11:14.025
I'm calling--

11:14.060 --> 11:15.927
The Board of Directors,
he's on it.

11:15.962 --> 11:17.562
He's in charge of fundraising
for the next two years,

11:17.596 --> 11:19.531
including the Heritage Fund.

11:19.565 --> 11:21.366
- You familiar with that?
- Yes, I am.

11:21.400 --> 11:22.601
Sorry to interrupt.

11:22.635 --> 11:25.137
No, it's no problem.

11:26.839 --> 11:35.413
Sorry.

11:35.447 --> 11:37.281
The irony of a view
you can't enjoy

11:37.315 --> 11:38.983
is not lost on me.

11:39.017 --> 11:40.884
I didn't want to give you
a different office

11:40.918 --> 11:42.452
just 'cause you can't
appreciate blue skies.

11:42.487 --> 11:45.121
By the way, we replicated your
D.P.D. workstation to the inch.

11:45.155 --> 11:47.156
Not exactly.

11:47.191 --> 11:49.058
You added
state-of-the-art speakers

11:49.092 --> 11:50.793
and some other goodies.

11:50.827 --> 11:52.628
Catered lunch at 1:00 p.m.

11:52.662 --> 11:56.432
You're in
the big leagues now.

11:56.466 --> 12:00.336
[Sighs]

12:00.371 --> 12:02.939
[Chuckles]

12:06.443 --> 12:09.246
Wow, you've really
made this place your own.

12:09.280 --> 12:10.914
And so quickly.

12:10.948 --> 12:12.616
Annie,
I had to sift through

12:12.651 --> 12:14.685
a lot of your NASA
interview footage.

12:14.719 --> 12:16.653
Next time try to
put the control question

12:16.688 --> 12:19.590
in the same place
during each interview.

12:19.624 --> 12:21.925
You varied it once.
Duly noted.

12:21.960 --> 12:24.695
In 84% of perjury cases,

12:24.729 --> 12:26.998
the subjects display
common physical behaviors,

12:27.032 --> 12:28.900
and in 70%
of those cases,

12:28.934 --> 12:30.568
they actually try
to hide themselves.

12:30.603 --> 12:33.438
They put up a physical
barrier like an arm.

12:33.472 --> 12:36.174
What are you working
on specifically right now?

12:36.208 --> 12:41.144
I, um, I supervise
a team of technicians

12:41.179 --> 12:43.580
in the satellite
maintenance office.

12:43.614 --> 12:44.748
That's it?

12:44.782 --> 12:46.249
That's our start.

12:46.283 --> 12:48.251
The arm across
his waist is the tell,

12:48.285 --> 12:51.621
so we dug deeper.

12:51.655 --> 12:54.457
The tensile quality
in his oculi and oris muscles

12:54.492 --> 12:57.027
is inconsistent
during this answer.

12:57.061 --> 12:59.196
An involuntary
sign of deceit.

12:59.231 --> 13:00.431
Or he was just nervous.

13:00.465 --> 13:01.666
He's got motive.

13:01.700 --> 13:03.201
NASA refused
to fund his project

13:03.235 --> 13:04.803
on satellite refueling
six months ago.

13:04.837 --> 13:06.538
His wife left him last year.

13:06.572 --> 13:08.540
And while he was initially
admitted to NASA

13:08.575 --> 13:10.142
through
the astronaut program,

13:10.176 --> 13:11.777
he never got
to go up in space.

13:11.811 --> 13:13.312
Of all the guys
I interviewed there,

13:13.347 --> 13:16.615
will was the only one cut
from genuine NASA cloth.

13:16.650 --> 13:19.618
NASA engineers are poorly
paid and underappreciated,

13:19.652 --> 13:22.487
two qualities that fit
the treasonous profile.

13:22.522 --> 13:24.022
We need to get him
under surveillance.

13:24.056 --> 13:26.024
That's N.S.A. purview.

13:26.058 --> 13:29.126
We'll get Joan to liaise
with Fort Meade.

13:29.160 --> 13:30.127
No.

13:30.161 --> 13:31.762
No way.
Absolutely not.

13:31.796 --> 13:33.964
A wiretap means
we're in bed with N.S.A.

13:33.998 --> 13:35.532
And they would control
the legacy switch.

13:35.566 --> 13:38.369
Sorry.

13:38.403 --> 13:40.871
Uh, an R1 wire transmitter

13:40.906 --> 13:42.540
could get around
the legacy switch.

13:42.574 --> 13:44.142
Supersede
the rule of law?

13:44.176 --> 13:46.411
Destroy our tenuous relationship
with justice and the N.S.A.?

13:46.446 --> 13:47.813
If you'll let me
just finish--

13:47.847 --> 13:49.314
No.

13:49.349 --> 13:51.016
Reva, you're new,

13:51.051 --> 13:52.518
so I'll let you in
on the way things work

13:52.552 --> 13:54.019
in my division.

13:54.054 --> 13:55.888
There is no socratic
method here.

13:55.922 --> 13:57.689
My decisions are final.

14:08.666 --> 14:09.866
You okay?

14:09.901 --> 14:13.169
Um, I'm fine.
I just have allergies.

14:13.204 --> 14:16.038
The pollen counts
are at 8.5.

14:16.073 --> 14:17.674
Just so you know,
you're not the first person

14:17.708 --> 14:19.575
Joan's bawled-out
on their first day.

14:19.610 --> 14:20.676
Really?

14:20.711 --> 14:22.678
She's actually kind of cool.

14:22.713 --> 14:26.582
Well, maybe not cool,
but not so bad

14:26.617 --> 14:28.551
once you figure her out.

14:28.585 --> 14:31.020
In D.S.T. we didn't have
to figure out people.

14:31.055 --> 14:35.558
We just generated files
and charts and studies and--

14:37.094 --> 14:39.429
I transferred here
to the D.P.D.

14:39.464 --> 14:41.465
because I wanted
more of a challenge.

14:41.499 --> 14:44.535
And clearly
I've gotten it.

14:44.569 --> 14:47.571
Around here, it's a bit more
of a two-way street,

14:47.605 --> 14:49.940
human intelligence
and hard facts.

14:49.974 --> 14:53.977
Yeah.

14:54.011 --> 14:55.978
What about
one-way surveillance?

14:56.013 --> 14:57.380
Bug their home?

14:57.414 --> 14:58.648
Why not?
We could do it ourselves.

14:58.683 --> 15:00.316
We'd only hear
one side of the phone call.

15:00.351 --> 15:01.451
But we'd hear everything

15:01.485 --> 15:02.853
that was going on
in their house.

15:02.887 --> 15:04.755
We'd maintain jurisdiction
over the investigation,

15:04.789 --> 15:06.357
and we wouldn't have
to interface with N.S.A.

15:06.391 --> 15:07.491
That'll work.

15:07.526 --> 15:10.594
How should we get
inside their house?

15:10.629 --> 15:12.831
Create a diversion?
Call in a bomb threat?

15:12.865 --> 15:14.499
No, that's likely
to tip off the FBI,

15:14.534 --> 15:15.500
and we don't want that.

15:15.535 --> 15:18.404
How 'bout this?

15:18.438 --> 15:21.106
What are you doing?

15:21.141 --> 15:25.811
Are you calling
the target?

15:25.845 --> 15:27.379
- Hello.
- Hey, is this Will?

15:27.413 --> 15:28.680
Yes.
Who's this?

15:28.715 --> 15:31.250
This is Annie Walker
from the Smithsonian.

15:31.284 --> 15:33.052
I filmed you for Mars day.

15:33.086 --> 15:35.488
If was wondering if I couldn't
drop off a photo we have here

15:35.522 --> 15:38.791
as a small thank you
for doing our piece.

15:38.825 --> 15:40.293
- Today?
- Yeah, today'd be great.

15:40.327 --> 15:42.728
I could even take
you guys out for a bite.

15:42.763 --> 15:44.697
Charlie and I were planning
to grill on the rooftop.

15:44.731 --> 15:47.166
Nothing special of course.
You're welcome to come.

15:47.200 --> 15:48.734
Around 6:30 or 7:00?

15:48.769 --> 15:50.870
I love a good barbecue.

15:50.904 --> 15:55.141
I'll see you tonight.

15:55.175 --> 15:56.676
Annie, when you were
up at NASA,

15:56.710 --> 15:58.444
did anything seem
out of the ordinary?

15:58.478 --> 16:02.015
Uh, P.R. rep asked me
what I was doing,

16:02.049 --> 16:03.183
but I handled it.

16:03.217 --> 16:05.719
You handled it?

16:05.753 --> 16:07.020
Did it ever occur to you

16:07.054 --> 16:10.056
that you might have blown
your cover yesterday?

16:10.090 --> 16:11.958
I mean, what are the chances
of them having a barbecue

16:11.992 --> 16:14.828
the night you invite
yourself over?

16:14.862 --> 16:17.431
This is a trap.

16:26.281 --> 16:29.717
You get all that?

16:29.751 --> 16:31.284
Yes.

16:31.319 --> 16:33.587
And are we responding
to a request

16:33.621 --> 16:35.922
to declassify these three
Afghanistan missions?

16:35.957 --> 16:37.057
This is voluntary.

16:37.091 --> 16:38.392
It's part of
my transparency push.

16:38.426 --> 16:39.726
Some of our assets
in Kashmir

16:39.760 --> 16:41.628
have used their influence
to open up the region.

16:41.663 --> 16:42.929
Yes, sir.

16:42.964 --> 16:44.264
And, Auggie,

16:44.298 --> 16:45.932
have some fun with this.

16:45.966 --> 16:49.235
We built
a school for girls.

16:49.270 --> 16:52.338
It's the feel-good hit
of the summer.

16:52.372 --> 16:53.606
Yes, sir.

17:02.415 --> 17:03.615
[Knocks]

17:03.650 --> 17:05.617
Hey.

17:05.651 --> 17:07.786
Come on in.

17:14.861 --> 17:16.395
Apollo 15.

17:16.429 --> 17:17.496
You remembered.

17:17.531 --> 17:19.499
I thought you'd
appreciate it.

17:19.532 --> 17:21.166
Thank you.

17:21.201 --> 17:23.069
I swear, the sun
was brighter back then.

17:23.104 --> 17:24.671
I'm sure that's
just 'cause Florida

17:24.704 --> 17:27.607
is closer
to the equator.

17:27.642 --> 17:31.344
Charlie is upstairs
lighting the coals.

17:31.379 --> 17:32.679
Can I get you
something to drink?

17:32.713 --> 17:36.148
- Beer?
- Sure.

17:36.182 --> 17:39.918
[Upbeat music]

17:39.952 --> 17:47.325
♪ ♪

17:48.528 --> 17:50.028
It's clean.

17:50.062 --> 17:52.130
It's just we're not
big folders around here.

17:52.164 --> 17:53.798
No judgment.

17:53.832 --> 17:54.999
Should we go upstairs?

17:55.033 --> 17:57.468
I'm hungry too.
Let's go.

18:00.205 --> 18:01.438
Remember, Annie,

18:01.473 --> 18:03.040
you need to give Jai
coverage in the apartment

18:03.074 --> 18:06.010
from 7:00 to 7:15 for
the surveillance installation.

18:06.044 --> 18:09.413
Don't come down from the roof
until 7:15.

18:09.447 --> 18:12.349
First star of the night, dad.
Antares beat Scorpio.

18:12.384 --> 18:15.018
Oh, there's Boötes.

18:15.053 --> 18:17.421
- I can just see Spica.
- Where?

18:19.157 --> 18:21.492
It's nice
you guys take the time

18:21.526 --> 18:23.194
to come and do this
once in a while.

18:23.228 --> 18:24.829
Not just once
in a while.

18:24.863 --> 18:27.031
I come home from work to look
at the stars with Charlie

18:27.065 --> 18:29.400
every night
no matter what.

18:29.434 --> 18:31.135
Let's eat.

18:31.169 --> 18:34.538
Delphinus was the first
constellation I ever learned.

18:34.572 --> 18:35.839
My dad taught me.

18:35.874 --> 18:37.708
I got chicken pox

18:37.742 --> 18:39.443
the first day
before third grade.

18:39.477 --> 18:42.045
He carried me out
into the backyard,

18:42.080 --> 18:43.313
pointed straight up,

18:43.348 --> 18:45.916
and told me the story
of Delphinus.

18:45.951 --> 18:47.051
So every autumn
when you look

18:47.085 --> 18:48.687
at the small cluster
of Delphinus,

18:48.721 --> 18:49.954
you must think of him.

18:49.989 --> 18:51.522
Yeah, I do.

19:04.771 --> 19:06.973
[Laughter]

19:07.007 --> 19:08.808
Charlie,
set up the telescope.

19:08.842 --> 19:11.043
Come on.

19:12.446 --> 19:14.948
Oh, wow.

19:16.417 --> 19:19.686
Are, uh, you married
or anything?

19:19.720 --> 19:22.788
Uh, not that I know of.

19:22.823 --> 19:24.290
You should hang out
with my dad.

19:24.324 --> 19:25.458
He's really cool.

19:25.492 --> 19:26.793
Whoa.

19:26.827 --> 19:29.662
I mean, he can be kind of
a dork sometimes,

19:29.697 --> 19:32.332
but he built
this telescope.

19:32.367 --> 19:34.468
It is impressive.

19:34.502 --> 19:36.604
I know our apartment
looks really depressing,

19:36.638 --> 19:40.007
but it's just 'cause my dad
never asks for a raise.

19:40.042 --> 19:41.742
He doesn't believe
in asking for anything.

19:41.777 --> 19:43.077
He's really proud
about that.

19:43.111 --> 19:45.680
- What about you?
- Nah, not so much.

19:45.714 --> 19:47.748
I've got my eye
on a really sweet Vespa.

19:47.783 --> 19:49.250
[Laughs]
Oh.

19:49.284 --> 19:51.819
[Thunder rumbles]

19:51.854 --> 19:55.856
Wow, the weatherman's
finally right.

19:55.891 --> 19:57.324
Storm's on its way.

19:57.359 --> 20:00.928
Better get downstairs.

20:00.962 --> 20:02.629
Actually,
I'm still hungry.

20:02.663 --> 20:04.898
Could I have
one more bratwurst?

20:09.370 --> 20:11.105
Yeah, I got you
loud and clear.

20:11.139 --> 20:13.107
Walking through right now

20:13.141 --> 20:14.875
talking out loud
like a crazy person.

20:14.910 --> 20:18.279
You got that?

20:18.314 --> 20:20.015
Okay, I'm gonna set one more.
It's all we've got time for.

20:21.918 --> 20:23.052
This was really good.

20:23.086 --> 20:24.186
You can take
that downstairs.

20:24.220 --> 20:25.621
You don't have to eat it
out in the rain.

20:25.655 --> 20:26.621
Oh.

20:26.656 --> 20:28.657
[Thunder rumbles]

20:38.600 --> 20:40.601
Just made it.

20:44.205 --> 20:46.574
Oh, uh, I left
my sweater upstairs.

20:46.608 --> 20:48.409
You guys head on down.
I'll get it.

20:48.443 --> 20:50.077
Thanks, Charlie.

21:08.799 --> 21:10.599
Feel great.

21:10.634 --> 21:12.534
Had a light supper.

21:12.569 --> 21:14.036
Went to bed early.
I slept like a rock.

21:14.070 --> 21:16.171
Yeah, I ate too much
and went to bed late.

21:16.206 --> 21:18.073
But thanks.

21:18.107 --> 21:20.242
Hey, can I ask you something?
Sure.

21:20.276 --> 21:22.043
Is everything okay
with you and Michael?

21:22.077 --> 21:24.545
I know he's been
traveling a lot.

21:24.580 --> 21:25.846
It's fine.

21:25.881 --> 21:29.016
I mean, it's weird.
It's hard to explain.

21:29.050 --> 21:30.685
Try me.

21:30.719 --> 21:31.920
I mean, it's nothing
earth-shattering.

21:31.954 --> 21:35.591
- It's just...
- Danielle, what is it?

21:35.625 --> 21:37.727
I don't miss him much.

21:37.761 --> 21:39.062
At all.

21:39.096 --> 21:41.131
- Danielle, I'm so--
- No, it's fine.

21:41.166 --> 21:43.634
That's what's so crazy.
I'm fine.

21:43.668 --> 21:45.435
What happened?

21:45.470 --> 21:47.771
I don't know.

21:47.805 --> 21:49.005
[Sighs]

21:49.040 --> 21:51.341
Do you think
it's possible to...

21:51.375 --> 21:54.344
slowly fall out of love
with someone?

21:54.378 --> 21:57.114
[Dramatic music]

21:57.148 --> 21:59.950
♪ ♪

21:59.984 --> 22:01.618
Any thoughts? Hello?

22:01.653 --> 22:04.621
Let's keep running
and talking.

22:04.655 --> 22:07.824
[Dramatic music]

22:07.858 --> 22:10.426
So I don't know whether
I should talk to Michael.

22:10.461 --> 22:12.429
Annie.

22:12.463 --> 22:14.097
[Laughs]

22:14.131 --> 22:15.465
Hey, slow down!

22:15.499 --> 22:17.133
I just wanna finish.
You wanna win!

22:17.167 --> 22:19.001
Sorry.

22:23.539 --> 22:24.840
Danielle,
I wanna talk about this,

22:24.874 --> 22:27.476
but I realized I just dropped
my phone back there.

22:27.510 --> 22:28.811
The museum's
gonna kill me.

22:28.845 --> 22:30.179
It has everyone's
home number on it.

22:30.213 --> 22:33.182
- Well, I'll help you.
- No, uh, don't.

22:33.217 --> 22:34.250
Go home.

22:34.285 --> 22:36.153
Please.

22:36.187 --> 22:37.988
The girls have to
get ready for school.

22:38.022 --> 22:39.489
- Well, I'll call--
- No, you can't.

22:39.524 --> 22:40.791
'Cause you
don't have your phone,

22:40.825 --> 22:42.460
and I dropped mine.

22:42.494 --> 22:44.529
I'll be careful.
I promise.

22:44.563 --> 22:46.063
Okay.

22:50.168 --> 22:52.502
[Dramatic, suspenseful music]

22:52.536 --> 22:54.938
♪ ♪

23:12.555 --> 23:15.456
[Tires screech,
horn honks]

23:15.491 --> 23:16.991
[Tires screech]

23:17.026 --> 23:18.693
[Crash]

23:18.728 --> 23:19.995
[Horn honks]

23:24.768 --> 23:27.002
[Panting]

23:34.014 --> 23:35.848
[Line ringing]

23:35.882 --> 23:38.351
- Hey, Annie.
- I was surveilled this morning.

23:38.385 --> 23:41.386
I need you to get in touch
with Rock Creek Park police

23:41.421 --> 23:42.654
and see if anyone I.D.'d

23:42.688 --> 23:45.590
a female involved
in a parkway pileup.

23:45.624 --> 23:47.491
Blue top
with a long braid.

23:47.526 --> 23:48.559
Okay, will do.

23:48.593 --> 23:51.328
As for you,
protocol directive 2408.

23:51.362 --> 23:53.229
Got it.
I'll watch my tail.

23:53.264 --> 23:55.065
No. That means
you shouldn't come in today.

23:55.099 --> 23:57.000
[Laughs]
Not gonna happen.

24:00.705 --> 24:03.474
I'm in sticker shock.

24:03.508 --> 24:05.143
It's not even itemized.

24:05.177 --> 24:07.546
Neither are
our bills to Congress.

24:07.580 --> 24:09.281
He knew we had
nowhere else to turn,

24:09.315 --> 24:11.049
he knew we needed
a fat cat attorney,

24:11.084 --> 24:13.086
and he got us to dip
into our retirement funds

24:13.120 --> 24:14.887
for a tennis vacation
in Hilton Head?

24:14.922 --> 24:16.755
Yeah,
don't personalize it.

24:16.790 --> 24:19.058
I was wrong...

24:19.092 --> 24:21.760
to insist
that we hire him.

24:21.794 --> 24:24.363
So what should we do?

24:24.397 --> 24:28.066
I need you to be
every bit as gallant

24:28.100 --> 24:29.567
as I know you can be.

24:29.602 --> 24:30.902
This doesn't sound good.

24:30.936 --> 24:33.237
I need you to pay him,

24:33.272 --> 24:36.240
and then I need you
to fire him.

24:36.274 --> 24:37.742
Please.

24:39.178 --> 24:41.413
[Sighs]

24:41.447 --> 24:43.749
- I thought you--
- I wasn't tailed.

24:43.783 --> 24:45.017
How can you be sure?

24:45.051 --> 24:47.019
I took three buses,
two Metro lines,

24:47.054 --> 24:48.521
and the Agency jitney
dropped me off

24:48.555 --> 24:49.589
at the front door.

24:49.623 --> 24:50.957
All in all,

24:50.991 --> 24:52.125
I'd say public transportation's
a better deal

24:52.159 --> 24:53.459
than my parking spot.
[Laughs]

24:53.494 --> 24:55.461
Your boy Will
has an active nightlife.

24:55.496 --> 24:56.763
[Beep]

24:56.797 --> 24:58.765
That was the woman
who tailed me in the park.

24:58.799 --> 25:00.266
She was with Will?

25:00.300 --> 25:02.668
Last night, almost
immediately after you left.

25:02.702 --> 25:05.303
Then will came back home
and we got this.

25:05.338 --> 25:06.638
[Beep]

25:06.672 --> 25:08.974
I have another drop.
Same time and place.

25:10.009 --> 25:12.344
Will's our guy.

25:20.653 --> 25:22.187
Auggie.

25:22.221 --> 25:25.091
This press release
about our missions, the school,

25:25.125 --> 25:27.326
my efforts
to open up the Agency...

25:27.361 --> 25:28.494
Yes, sir.

25:28.528 --> 25:30.497
It reads like
<i>Crime and Punishment,</i>

25:30.531 --> 25:31.998
except with
no information in it.

25:32.033 --> 25:34.501
You're maddeningly obtuse.

25:34.535 --> 25:36.336
If we're gonna depress
the hell out of everyone,

25:36.371 --> 25:39.305
let's not bother voluntarily
declassifying anything.

25:40.341 --> 25:42.008
I mean, Auggie...

25:42.043 --> 25:44.677
We built a girls' school.

25:44.711 --> 25:45.978
A girls' school.

25:46.012 --> 25:47.480
And I included that.

25:47.514 --> 25:49.482
Along with vague,
conditional information

25:49.516 --> 25:52.385
about the purpose
of the school itself.

25:52.419 --> 25:54.553
Let me save you
some cat-and-mouse.

25:54.588 --> 25:56.188
Girls will show up.

25:56.222 --> 25:58.023
They will learn.

25:58.057 --> 25:59.858
Lives will improve.

25:59.893 --> 26:02.161
It's straightforward.

26:02.195 --> 26:04.596
Now, I underestimated
how difficult a transition

26:04.631 --> 26:07.032
it would be for a good
covert operative like yourself,

26:07.066 --> 26:10.203
especially one with such talent
on the battlefield.

26:10.237 --> 26:12.004
It's not difficult, sir.

26:12.039 --> 26:13.839
I'm asking you
to run against every instinct

26:13.873 --> 26:15.040
to maintain secrecy.

26:15.075 --> 26:17.209
I learned those skills.

26:17.244 --> 26:18.577
I can unlearn them.

26:18.612 --> 26:21.079
Well,
unlearn them quick.

26:21.114 --> 26:22.814
The press conference
is tomorrow.

26:35.229 --> 26:37.363
[Sighs]

26:37.398 --> 26:40.700
Annie Walker
and icy-hot menthol.

26:40.735 --> 26:42.369
[Laughs]

26:42.403 --> 26:45.038
Marathon training
is no picnic.

26:45.072 --> 26:47.374
Hey, these new digs

26:47.408 --> 26:48.842
are incredible.

26:48.876 --> 26:50.677
Yeah, I've got
my own thermostat.

26:50.711 --> 26:52.245
And free lunch.

26:52.279 --> 26:53.913
All I ever wanted
was a job with free food.

26:53.948 --> 26:57.551
But you're not here
to talk about my job, are you?

26:57.585 --> 26:59.786
The D.P.D. has their
NASA traitor dead to rights--

26:59.820 --> 27:02.122
phone calls,
surveillance photos--

27:02.156 --> 27:04.457
but something about it
does not line up.

27:04.492 --> 27:05.592
Talk to Reva.

27:05.626 --> 27:07.427
I vetted her with Joan.
She's good.

27:07.461 --> 27:09.029
- She's not you.
- Annie.

27:09.063 --> 27:10.730
I'd love to help you,
but I can't.

27:10.765 --> 27:14.100
What do you mean you can't?
You always know what to do.

27:18.539 --> 27:20.774
I just bombed out on
my first assignment for Arthur,

27:20.808 --> 27:24.310
and I've gotta turn it around
by the end of the day.

27:27.514 --> 27:31.150
You were the first friend
I ever made at this Agency...

27:31.184 --> 27:33.385
And no one
I have met here

27:33.419 --> 27:36.388
has impressed me
more since.

27:36.422 --> 27:39.626
You're gonna do great
at this job.

27:45.234 --> 27:47.235
[Door bangs shut]

27:54.077 --> 27:55.878
I wanna make it clear
we're just talking.

27:55.913 --> 27:58.014
You're free to go
at any time.

27:58.048 --> 27:59.682
In the way
I'm free to not take

27:59.716 --> 28:01.851
the field sobriety test?

28:01.885 --> 28:03.853
Meaning what?

28:03.888 --> 28:06.122
Meaning that,
by not talking,

28:06.157 --> 28:08.325
it's a presumption
of guilt.

28:09.594 --> 28:12.262
We can talk about talking,

28:12.296 --> 28:15.098
or we can talk.

28:17.902 --> 28:19.837
Or we can sit
and not talk.

28:21.407 --> 28:22.907
I didn't know
who they were at first.

28:22.941 --> 28:25.744
- You know who they are now?
- Colombian rebels.

28:25.778 --> 28:27.579
I'm going to advise you
to get an attorney...

28:27.613 --> 28:29.415
- [Sighs]
- Because we're gonna have to

28:29.449 --> 28:31.150
hand our investigation
over to the Feds.

28:33.207 --> 28:34.741
I'll tell you
everything.

28:34.776 --> 28:36.777
I'm tired of lying.

28:38.353 --> 28:39.786
How did the 
Colombians make you?

28:41.157 --> 28:42.590
I don't understand.

28:42.625 --> 28:44.425
How did they turn you?

28:44.459 --> 28:46.828
How did they convince you
to spy for them?

28:46.862 --> 28:50.597
I was at a science fair
of Charlie's.

28:50.632 --> 28:54.601
He was a finalist
in the national competition.

28:54.636 --> 28:56.570
She was a very attractive
American woman

28:56.604 --> 28:58.571
who said she was
from the private sector.

28:58.606 --> 29:00.273
She said her company
had heard of my work

29:00.307 --> 29:02.108
and that no price
was too high

29:02.143 --> 29:03.843
to woo me away
from NASA.

29:03.878 --> 29:05.178
She works for FARC.

29:05.212 --> 29:06.412
I know that now.

29:06.446 --> 29:08.080
I knew that her company
was coming at me

29:08.115 --> 29:10.083
with a strategy
of seduction, but I--

29:10.117 --> 29:12.019
I just didn't care.

29:12.053 --> 29:13.854
After a couple
of rough years

29:13.889 --> 29:15.757
both personally
and professionally,

29:15.791 --> 29:17.692
she was a tonic.

29:17.726 --> 29:18.860
Then what happened?

29:18.894 --> 29:21.029
Then I met her again...

29:21.063 --> 29:22.864
This time
at the planetarium.

29:22.898 --> 29:25.200
She asked me
for a manual

29:25.235 --> 29:29.037
that I'd written on, uh,
satellite maintenance.

29:29.072 --> 29:30.972
Which they
could reverse engineer.

29:32.308 --> 29:33.775
So after you
gave her the manual,

29:33.809 --> 29:35.777
is that when she revealed
who she worked for?

29:35.811 --> 29:37.945
[Sighs] By that time,
they had their hooks in me.

29:37.980 --> 29:39.280
They blackmailed me
for more information

29:39.314 --> 29:40.448
about the satellite.

29:40.482 --> 29:41.649
I was--
I was trapped.

29:41.683 --> 29:43.484
You weren't trapped.

29:43.518 --> 29:45.018
You could have
come to us

29:45.053 --> 29:46.686
after handing over
that first manual,

29:46.721 --> 29:49.056
but you chose not to.

29:51.994 --> 29:53.661
I'm sorry.

30:03.572 --> 30:04.839
You wanna talk
about it?

30:04.874 --> 30:07.676
There's nothing
really to say.

30:07.710 --> 30:09.611
Maybe it's
just a temporary lull

30:09.646 --> 30:11.246
or a passing funk.

30:14.917 --> 30:16.485
Michael's a good father.

30:16.519 --> 30:19.988
You always see the best
in everyone.

30:20.023 --> 30:22.891
- Maybe I'm naive.
- No.

30:22.925 --> 30:25.726
I just need to
take a beat and refocus.

30:27.729 --> 30:30.264
Why don't you go
for a romantic night out?

30:30.299 --> 30:32.933
I'll watch the girls
this weekend.

30:33.969 --> 30:35.636
I could do that.

30:39.775 --> 30:41.876
[Clears throat]

30:41.910 --> 30:43.544
I'm just into
Will's finances.

30:43.578 --> 30:45.680
He listed NASA
as a beneficiary

30:45.714 --> 30:47.448
of part of his 401k.

30:47.483 --> 30:48.583
So?

30:48.617 --> 30:49.917
So this is not a guy

30:49.952 --> 30:51.752
who hates
his institution.

30:51.786 --> 30:55.256
Annie, you helped the D.P.D.
nail NASA's mole, okay?

30:55.290 --> 30:58.126
It's in the Feds' hands now.
Can we move on?

30:58.160 --> 31:01.363
Uh, normally this is the time
where my former tech op

31:01.397 --> 31:04.099
would encourage me,
support my gut instinct,

31:04.133 --> 31:06.034
and assist in my research.

31:08.104 --> 31:11.173
Have you heard
of the hummingbird project?

31:11.207 --> 31:12.574
Was that the one
two years ago

31:12.608 --> 31:15.210
where D.S.T. was making
surveillance birds?

31:15.244 --> 31:16.878
Yes, remote-controlled
hummingbirds

31:16.913 --> 31:19.314
that could monitor
outdoor conversations.

31:20.316 --> 31:22.784
I was behind that.

31:22.818 --> 31:26.520
And even after it failed
a very critical test run

31:26.555 --> 31:27.922
due to interference,

31:27.956 --> 31:30.726
I kept pushing it.
I couldn't let it go.

31:30.760 --> 31:32.261
Well, it sounds
like a cool idea.

31:32.295 --> 31:33.929
Well, it was.

31:33.963 --> 31:35.431
Until we took it out
to Camp Peary

31:35.465 --> 31:36.899
for a second test run.

31:36.933 --> 31:38.401
There was one thing
we didn't count on,

31:38.435 --> 31:40.236
was the weather.

31:40.271 --> 31:41.738
I mean,
when the wind blew,

31:41.773 --> 31:43.507
we couldn't control
the damn things.

31:43.541 --> 31:45.843
My blind faith
in that project

31:45.877 --> 31:48.879
set me back two years
at the Agency.

31:50.014 --> 31:53.016
So...take some advice
from me

31:53.050 --> 31:55.618
and get out of
your own way.

31:55.652 --> 31:57.619
We're done
with the NASA operation.

31:57.654 --> 32:01.457
Move on, okay?

32:01.491 --> 32:03.259
You know what I get
from that story?

32:04.861 --> 32:06.829
You were fired up
about something.

32:09.066 --> 32:14.103
[Departing footsteps]

32:15.906 --> 32:17.774
Auggie, you are
the Ernest Hemingway

32:17.808 --> 32:19.109
of good news.

32:19.143 --> 32:20.878
Turns out I was right.
You're a natural at this.

32:20.912 --> 32:22.213
[Exhales]

32:22.247 --> 32:23.882
You're a quick study.

32:23.916 --> 32:26.218
You're gonna help move
the Agency into a new era.

32:26.252 --> 32:29.154
[Clattering]

32:29.188 --> 32:31.990
Reporters are like
tigers in captivity--

32:32.024 --> 32:33.358
if you wanna clean
the cage,

32:33.393 --> 32:36.795
you gotta distract 'em
with a piece of meat.

32:36.830 --> 32:39.732
Many good operatives
have come in from the cold.

32:39.766 --> 32:41.533
Yes, sir.

32:41.568 --> 32:43.368
There is a life,

32:43.403 --> 32:46.404
a fulfilling life,
for an overt officer, Auggie.

32:51.378 --> 32:54.180
[Chattering,
camera shutters clicking]

32:54.214 --> 32:56.549
Come on, Auggie.
It's time.

32:57.752 --> 33:00.320
Micro-expressions
don't lie, right?

33:00.355 --> 33:03.323
Well, I don't like
to use absolutes, but yes,

33:03.358 --> 33:04.692
statistically,
micro-expressions

33:04.726 --> 33:06.160
are excellent baselines
of truthfulness.

33:06.195 --> 33:07.495
And putting up
a physical barrier,

33:07.529 --> 33:09.163
like your arm
or a coffee cup,

33:09.197 --> 33:11.165
means a lie, right?

33:11.199 --> 33:14.001
- Right.
- Okay.

33:15.970 --> 33:17.037
[Beep]

33:17.071 --> 33:18.372
How did they turn you?

33:18.406 --> 33:21.274
How did they convince you
to spy for them?

33:21.309 --> 33:23.776
I was at a science fair
for Charlie.

33:23.811 --> 33:25.044
He was a, uh,

33:25.079 --> 33:28.013
a finalist
in the national competition.

33:28.048 --> 33:30.450
Wait a second.

33:30.484 --> 33:32.986
That's his tell.
[Beeping]

33:33.021 --> 33:34.221
Right?

33:34.255 --> 33:36.323
You're right.
He's lying.

33:36.357 --> 33:38.158
Exactly.

33:38.193 --> 33:41.262
How could he be lying
both times?

33:43.566 --> 33:46.168
[Door clicks open]

33:48.337 --> 33:50.005
[Chuckles]

33:51.340 --> 33:53.541
Somehow I knew
that a beautiful filmmaker

33:53.576 --> 33:57.546
who loves space
was too good to be true.

33:57.580 --> 33:59.682
What happened
to the aspiring astronaut?

33:59.716 --> 34:00.916
Annie,

34:00.951 --> 34:03.886
in the scope of things,
I didn't ruin the world.

34:03.920 --> 34:06.889
Life--or the expansion of
the galaxy, for that matter--

34:06.923 --> 34:09.491
continues to go on
for billions of years,

34:09.525 --> 34:11.993
with or without me.

34:12.027 --> 34:14.661
We're just
a pale-blue dot.

34:16.031 --> 34:17.331
Charlie quoted Carl Sagan

34:17.366 --> 34:19.533
when he was talking
about pioneer 10.

34:21.369 --> 34:24.004
It wasn't you they made
at the science fair.

34:24.039 --> 34:26.841
It was Charlie...

34:26.875 --> 34:28.877
Wasn't it?

34:31.547 --> 34:33.315
He was only a boy.

34:33.349 --> 34:37.284
A very smart
16-year-old boy.

34:37.320 --> 34:39.655
And then she came along.

34:41.458 --> 34:42.925
That's all it took
to snag a kid

34:42.960 --> 34:44.928
with his own ambitions,

34:44.962 --> 34:47.496
who also wanted his old man
to be a hero again.

34:47.531 --> 34:49.498
How'd he get
the information?

34:49.533 --> 34:51.701
At first
it was just my resume.

34:51.735 --> 34:54.536
Then it was a paper
I wrote.

34:54.571 --> 34:56.038
He thought
he was giving my work

34:56.072 --> 34:59.507
to someone
in the private sector.

34:59.542 --> 35:01.676
They told him that,
just by doing that,

35:01.711 --> 35:04.212
he had violated
the State Secrets Act,

35:04.246 --> 35:06.214
and they just kept
asking for more.

35:06.248 --> 35:08.049
When did they have you?

35:08.084 --> 35:10.386
As soon
as Charlie told me.

35:10.420 --> 35:11.787
I took over
the relationship.

35:11.822 --> 35:14.858
I gave them the information
about the satellites, and...

35:14.892 --> 35:16.860
I didn't know
what else to do.

35:16.894 --> 35:18.729
What did Charlie
think was happening?

35:20.933 --> 35:23.901
He thought
I'd fixed it all.

35:23.936 --> 35:27.405
He thought things
were back to normal.

35:27.440 --> 35:29.774
It's been hard
since his mother left.

35:32.378 --> 35:33.878
But it wasn't over,
was it?

35:33.913 --> 35:35.647
No.

35:35.681 --> 35:37.815
Why the phone call?

35:40.218 --> 35:42.019
When I walked you
out of the building

35:42.053 --> 35:44.387
after the barbecue...

35:44.422 --> 35:46.489
I saw they left me
a signal.

35:46.524 --> 35:48.525
There was a bike

35:48.559 --> 35:50.027
locked up
to the bus stop.

35:50.061 --> 35:52.763
That meant they wanted me
to meet them immediately.

35:53.932 --> 35:55.266
What did they say
at the meeting?

35:55.301 --> 35:58.070
Oh, they thought
you might be on to me.

35:58.104 --> 35:59.538
When you walked
in the building,

35:59.572 --> 36:01.706
they said someone
followed you in

36:01.741 --> 36:03.608
and climbed out
the fire escape

36:03.643 --> 36:06.344
just when we came down
from the rooftop.

36:06.379 --> 36:08.613
They assumed
that you'd bugged my place.

36:08.648 --> 36:10.449
Then why
would you go home

36:10.483 --> 36:12.618
and make
an incriminating phone call?

36:12.652 --> 36:15.387
[Sighs]

36:15.422 --> 36:17.222
[Chuckles]

36:17.257 --> 36:20.725
Wait...you were trying
to get caught?

36:20.759 --> 36:23.360
That was just a message
I left on my own voicemail.

36:23.395 --> 36:24.695
Once you were out to us,

36:24.729 --> 36:26.363
FARC's pipeline
to NASA's information

36:26.397 --> 36:27.564
would be shut down.

36:27.599 --> 36:29.733
And Charlie
would be useless to them.

36:29.768 --> 36:31.735
Well, what was
your contingency plan?

36:31.770 --> 36:33.604
All of this.

36:33.638 --> 36:37.441
[Exhales]
This wasn't a space mission.

36:37.476 --> 36:39.176
I had to protect my son,

36:39.211 --> 36:40.812
no matter what the cost.

36:44.651 --> 36:46.152
[Phone rings]

36:49.255 --> 36:50.556
Reva.

36:50.590 --> 36:53.726
Annie Walker.
I remember you.

36:53.760 --> 36:54.761
Auggie.

36:54.795 --> 36:56.796
I'm back.

36:57.931 --> 36:59.766
[Sighs] Because you
missed me so much?

36:59.800 --> 37:01.267
[Laughs]
Ah, you're good,

37:01.302 --> 37:02.602
but you're not
that good.

37:02.636 --> 37:04.403
I wasn't ready
to blow my cover.

37:04.438 --> 37:07.406
Besides, you are clearly
helpless without me.

37:07.441 --> 37:10.476
Completely
and utterly helpless.

37:10.510 --> 37:13.011
Are you read in?
Yeah. It's not over, Annie.

37:13.046 --> 37:14.846
- Why?
- Charlie made a call.

37:14.881 --> 37:17.116
He offered to give up everything
about his dad's research

37:17.150 --> 37:18.784
on satellite
rendezvous capacities

37:18.818 --> 37:19.952
if they'll let will go.

37:19.986 --> 37:21.954
He thinks will
is being held by FARC?

37:21.988 --> 37:24.923
You gotta get to him
before they do.

37:28.810 --> 37:30.344
[tires screech]

37:30.378 --> 37:32.379
[Suspenseful music]

37:32.413 --> 37:34.682
♪ ♪

37:36.985 --> 37:39.053
Charlie,
listen to me.

37:39.087 --> 37:41.222
Your dad's safe.
We wanna help you.

37:41.257 --> 37:44.192
He told us about FARC.
I'm here to protect you.

37:44.227 --> 37:47.029
88 constellations

37:47.063 --> 37:51.534
move across the sky
each year.

37:51.568 --> 37:53.770
Cast your eyes upward

37:53.804 --> 37:56.573
toward
the Northern Hemisphere,

37:56.607 --> 38:00.444
and we will explore
just one part

38:00.478 --> 38:04.748
of the celestial field
that has mesmerized...

38:11.322 --> 38:14.325
[Suspenseful music]

38:14.359 --> 38:17.661
♪ ♪

38:22.132 --> 38:23.466
[Lever clanks]

38:25.002 --> 38:26.335
[Approaching footsteps]

38:31.775 --> 38:33.775
Both: [Groaning]

38:33.810 --> 38:36.077
Charlie,
get the gun!

38:36.112 --> 38:40.415
Both: [Groaning]

38:55.165 --> 38:57.767
[Panting]

38:57.802 --> 39:01.639
It's over.
It's gonna be okay.

39:03.341 --> 39:06.443
[Sirens wailing]

39:06.477 --> 39:10.614
[Indistinct conversation
over police radio]

39:10.648 --> 39:12.949
Do you have
other relatives here?

39:12.984 --> 39:14.685
I mean,
who will you stay with?

39:14.719 --> 39:16.520
My grandma for now.

39:16.554 --> 39:21.358
Downside, lots of chores.
Upside, folded laundry.

39:21.392 --> 39:23.360
When can I see my dad?

39:23.394 --> 39:25.195
I don't know yet.

39:25.230 --> 39:26.864
What I do know
is I've never seen two people

39:26.898 --> 39:29.199
so loyal to each other.

39:29.234 --> 39:32.702
That will count
for something, Charlie.

39:32.737 --> 39:35.172
Come on. Let's call
your grandmother.

39:37.041 --> 39:38.575
Chet, we wanted
to talk to you.

39:38.610 --> 39:40.744
Look, there's no reason
to thank me.

39:40.778 --> 39:41.879
This is what I do.

39:41.913 --> 39:44.181
That's what we
wanted to talk about.

39:44.216 --> 39:46.217
I got him
in the third set.

39:47.453 --> 39:48.686
I'm not gonna lie to you.

39:48.721 --> 39:50.522
We could be having
a very different conversation

39:50.556 --> 39:53.024
if my tennis elbow
had flared up.

39:53.058 --> 39:55.260
We're talking about
why we hired you.

39:55.294 --> 39:57.262
Yeah, I know, Joanie.
No hearings.

39:57.296 --> 39:59.197
Who do you think
I was playing tennis <i>with?</i>

39:59.232 --> 40:00.498
I have no idea.

40:00.533 --> 40:03.201
The esteemed Senator
from Kentucky.

40:03.235 --> 40:04.702
Jensen?

40:04.736 --> 40:06.204
He told his committee
this morning

40:06.238 --> 40:10.708
there's no reason
to pursue an investigation.

40:11.977 --> 40:14.378
Get some sleep, chief.

40:22.920 --> 40:24.854
[Door bangs shut]

40:24.889 --> 40:26.790
[Upbeat pop music]

40:26.824 --> 40:29.125
[Laughter]

40:29.160 --> 40:30.627
To everything
in its place.

40:30.661 --> 40:31.695
Hear, hear.

40:31.729 --> 40:33.564
[Glasses clanking]

40:35.400 --> 40:36.867
Mm...

40:36.901 --> 40:38.302
What happens
to you now, Reva?

40:38.336 --> 40:40.971
Um, back to D.S.T.

40:41.005 --> 40:42.972
but with a bump
in pay grade.

40:43.007 --> 40:45.809
Hmm. They're nowhere near
as much fun as we are.

40:45.843 --> 40:47.377
But they're
more predictable.

40:47.411 --> 40:49.479
Oh, you say that
like it's a compliment.

40:49.514 --> 40:51.347
Time for more drinks.

40:51.382 --> 40:52.682
Oh...

40:52.716 --> 40:55.184
I gotta go.
I have a date.

40:55.218 --> 40:57.286
- Well, well.
- Ooh!

41:00.423 --> 41:02.691
Here it is.

41:04.228 --> 41:05.428
It's old.

41:05.462 --> 41:07.263
Did you find it?

41:07.298 --> 41:09.566
My dad gave it to me
for my birthday

41:09.600 --> 41:12.736
when I was just
a little older than you.

41:13.738 --> 41:15.038
You guys are really lucky,

41:15.073 --> 41:18.042
and not just because
I'm babysitting tonight.

41:18.076 --> 41:20.744
There's a really bright star
I'm gonna show you.

41:22.747 --> 41:24.214
Plus there's a story
to go with it.

41:24.248 --> 41:25.882
[Giggles]

41:25.916 --> 41:27.884
♪ La, la, la, la ♪

41:27.918 --> 41:29.552
♪ la, la, la, la ♪

41:29.586 --> 41:33.422
♪ the wrong miracle,
'cause all I wanted was you ♪

41:33.456 --> 41:36.891
♪ the wrong miracle,
but I guess it will do ♪

